Algorithmic accountability Use Machine Learning to guide GLM

  • Yang, Qian, and Zou (2018)
    • “[…] our approach can still be quite helpful due to its ability to extract additional information such as nonmonotonicity/ nonlinearity and important interaction .”
  • Henckaerts et al. (2021)
    • “an insurance company can still learn valuable information on how to form profitable portfolios from an internal, technical model”
    • “A possible approach would be to approximate a gradient boosting machine with a GLM […]. The gradient boosting machine can be used to discover the important variables and interactions between those variables, which can then be included in a GLM for deployment.”

Overview Machine learning vs GLM

Interpretability in this talk:

  • Regression: \(Y_i=m(X_i)+\varepsilon_i\)
    • \(X\qquad \rightarrow \qquad \widehat m (X) \qquad \rightarrow \qquad m (X)\) or \(Y\)
  • Interpretability is understanding the relationship between \(X\) and \(\widehat m (X)\)
Quality GLM Machine Learning
interpretable ✔ ✘
interactions manually ✔ ✔
interactions − ✔
variable selection/sparsity − ✔
non-linearity − ✔

  • Current machine learning algorithms are often highly flexible and can deal with interaction, sparsity and variable selection; but they are not interpretable .

  • GLMs are interpretable but lack flexibility. They also can not deal automatically with interactions, sparsity and variable selection.

Partial Dependence Plot Toy example I

  • Partial Dependence Plot is a global explanation because it explains features globally.
  • Partial Dependence Plot for feature \(k\): \(\xi_k(x_k)= \int \hat m(x) p_{-k}(x_{-k})\mathrm dx_{-k}.\)

Toy example I

  • \(X_1=\) Gender: policyholder’s gender (female or male);
  • \(X_2=\) Age: policyholder’s age (integer values from 18 to 65 );
  • \(X_3=\) Split: whether the policyholder splits its annual premium or not (yes or no);
  • \(X_4=\) Sport: whether the policyholder’s car is a sports car or not (yes or no).

Partial Dependence Plot Toy example I

  • Partial dependence can be misleading because they ignore interaction effects.
  • In abstract terms: partial dependence plots are projections into an additive space
    • (higher order) interactions are being ignored
    • Approximation is highly non-trivial and can be very unstable trough extrapolation, see Apley and Zhu (2020)

Shapley values Toy example II

Toy example II

\[m(x_1,x_2)=x_1+x_2 + 2x_1x_2.\]

The interventional SHAP value for the first feature is \[ \phi_1(x_1,x_2)=x_1-E[X_1]+x_1x_2 -E[X_1X_2]+x_1E[X_2]-x_2E[X_1]. \] If the features are standardized, i.e., \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) have mean zero and variance one, then

\[\phi_1(x_1,x_2)=x_1+x_1x_2 -\textrm{corr}(X_1,X_2).\]

  • Assume \(\textrm{corr}(X_1,X_2)=0.3\)
    • individual with \(x_1=1\) and \(x_2=-0.7\) would see a SHAP value of 0 for the first feature” \[\phi_1(1,-0.7) = 0.\]

A functional decomposition

Assume a data set with \(d\) features. Also assume that we can approximate the regression function \(m\) by a (q-th) order functional decomposition:

\[m(x) \approx m_0+\sum_{k=1}^d m_k(x_{k}) + \sum_{k_1<k_2} m_{k_1k_2}(x_{k_1},x_{k_2}) + \cdots +\sum_{k_1<\cdots <k_q} m_{k_1,\dots,k_q} (x_{k_1},\dots,x_{k_q}).\]

  • Optimal rates of convergence under the assumption that \(m\) has two continuous partial derivatives:
Model general general \(d\) \(d = 6\) Comparable sample sizes
Full model \(O_p(n^{-2/(d+4)})\) \(O_p(n^{-1/5})\) 1 000 000
Interaction (q) \(O_p(n^{-2/(q+4)})\) \(O_p(n^{-2/(q+4)})\) 1 000 -- 1 000 000
Interaction (q=2) \(O_p(n^{-1/3})\) \(O_p(n^{-1/3})\) 4 000
Additive (q=1) \(O_p(n^{-2/5})\) \(O_p(n^{-2/5})\) 1 000

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\) glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Marginal Identification

  • Components are not identified
  • We propose a new identification , we call marginal identification

Marginal Identification

For every \(S\subseteq \{1,\dots,d\}\) \[\sum_{T: T \cap S \neq \emptyset} \int m^\ast_T(x_T) p_{S}(x_{S}) \mathrm dx_S=0\]

Theorem

Given any initial estimator \(\hat m^{(0)}=\{\hat m^{(0)}_S | S\subseteq \{1,\dots,d\}\}\), there exists exactly one set of functions \(\hat m^\ast=\{\hat m^\ast_S | S\subseteq \{1,\dots,d\}\}\) satisfying the marginal constraint with \(\sum_S \hat m^\ast_S = \sum_S \hat m^{(0)}_S\). The functions are given by \[ \hat m^\ast_S (x_S)= \sum_{T \supseteq S} \sum_{T\setminus S \subseteq U\subseteq T}(-1)^{|S|-|T\setminus U|} \times \int \hat m^{(0)}_T(x_T) \hat p_U(x_U)\mathrm dx_U. \notag \] In particular \(\hat m^\ast\) does not depend on the particular identification of \(\hat m^{(0)}\).

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\) glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Marginal Identification

The are three reasons why the marginal identification is particularly interesting

  • Partial Dependence Plots
  • Interventional SHAP values
  • Fairness/ Discrimination-free pricing

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\) glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Marginal Identification: Partial Dependence Plots

A partial dependence plot, \(\xi_S\), is defined as \[\xi_k(x_S)= \int \hat m(x) p_{-S}(x_{-S})\mathrm dx_{-S}.\]

Corollary

If \(\hat m^{\ast}\) satisfies the marginal identification, then \[\xi_S=\sum_{U \subseteq S} \hat m_U^{\ast}.\] In particular if \(S\) is only one feature, i.e., \(S=\{k\}\), we have \[\xi_k(x_k)= \hat m_0^{\ast} + \hat m_k^\ast(x_k).\]

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\) glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Marginal Identification: Interventional SHAP values

Theorem

  • \(\hat m^{\ast}\) is decomposed with marginal identification satisfied
  • then, interventional SHAP values are weighted averages components
    • interaction component is equally split between involved features:

\[ \phi_k(x)= \hat m^{\ast}_k(x_k)+ \frac 1 2 \sum_j \hat m^{\ast}_{kj}(x_{kj}) + \cdots + \frac 1 d \hat m^{\ast}_{1,\dots,d}(x_{1,\dots,d}). \]

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\) glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Marginal Identification: SHAP values

Theorem

  • \(\hat m^{\ast}\) is decomposed with marginal identification satisfied
  • then, interventional SHAP values are weighted averages components
    • interaction component is equally split between involved features:

\[ \phi_k(x)= \hat m^{\ast}_k(x_k)+ \frac 1 2 \sum_j \hat m^{\ast}_{kj}(x_{kj}) + \cdots + \frac 1 d \hat m^{\ast}_{1,\dots,d}(x_{1,\dots,d}). \]

Related Literature (appeared some weeks after our preprint)

  • Bordt and Luxburg (2022) show that for every SHAP-value function there exists a one-to-one correspondence between SHAP values and an identification in a functional decomposition. But they do not provide explicit solutions.
  • Herren and Hahn (2022) describe an identification constraint that connects to observational SHAP.
  • We find an identification constraint that gives a one-to-one correspondence to interventional SHAP and provides a fast implementation for tree-based methods.

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\) glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Marginal Identification: fairness/discrimination-free pricing

  • Assume \(U\) is a set of protected features.

    • For example \(U=\{\text{gender, ethnicity}\}\).

  • Let \(U \cup V=\{1,\dots, d\}, U\cap V=\emptyset\).

  • The do-operator, \(do(X_V=x_V)\), removes all edges going into \(X_V\), ensuring counterfactual fairness [Kusner et al. (2017), see also Lindholm et al. (2022)

  • \(E[m(X) |\ do(X_V=x_V))\) does not use information contained in \(X_U\); neither directly nor indirectly.

  • Under the assumed causal structure we have \(E[m(X) |\ do(X_V=x_V)]= \int m(x) p_U(x_U) dx_U.\)

  • Under marginal identifiaction: \[\int \hat m^\ast(x) \hat p_U(x_U) dx_U= \sum_{S \subseteq V} \hat m^\ast_S(x_S),\] i.e., a “fair” estimator can be extracted from \(\hat m\) by dropping all components that include features in \(U\).

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\) glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Marginal Identification: Summary

Summary(Marginal Identification)

If \(m\) is identified via the marginal identification, \[ \hat m(x)=\hat m_0^\ast + \sum_j \hat m_j ^\ast (x_j) + \sum_{j<k} \hat m_{j,k} ^\ast (x_j,x_k)+ \cdots \] then

  • Interventional SHAP values are: \[ \phi_k(x)= \hat m^{\ast}_k(x_k)+ \frac 1 2 \sum_j \hat m^{\ast}_{kj}(x_{kj}) + \cdots \]

  • Partial dependence plots are: \[\xi_k(x_k)= \hat m_0^{\ast} + \hat m_k^\ast(x_k).\]

  • Fairness/Discrimination-free pricing: If \(S\) are protected variables and all components that contain a subset of \(S\) are dropped, we derive a de-biased estimator.

Interpretability Interventional SHAP: Toy example II

\[m(x_1,x_2)=x_1+x_2+x_1x_2\] If \(X_1, X_2\) have each mean zero and variance one, then

  • Marginal identification: \[ \begin{eqnarray} m_0&=&2corr(X_1,X_2) \\ m_1^\ast(x_1)&=& x_1 -2corr(X_1,X_2) \\ m_2^\ast(x_2)&=&x_2 - 2corr(X_1,X_2) \\ m_{12}^\ast(x_1,x_2)&=& 2x_1x_2 + 2corr(X_1,X_2). \end{eqnarray} \]

  • Partial dependence plot of \(x_1\) is \(m_1^\ast(x_1)\)

  • Interventional SHAP of \(x_1\) is \(m_1^\ast(x_1)+ 0.5 \times m_{12}^\ast(x_1,x_2)\)

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\)glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Open problems I

  • Caution: It is not clear if a method that estimates \(m\) well is also a good estimator for a selection of components {\(m_S\)}.

  • \(E[Y| do(X=x)]\) is the conditional expectation of Y given \(X\), with the impact of \(D\) on \(X\) eliminated. \[\begin{align}\label{marginal} E[Y| do(X=x)] =\int E[Y| X=x, D=d] p_D(d)\mathrm{d}d. \end{align}\]

  • naive way:

  • estimate \(E[Y| X=x, D=d]\) and \(p_D(d)\)

  • afterwards get \(\hat h(\boldsymbol{x})\) (by (numerically) evaluating the integral).

  • Unfortunately, the resulting estimator will most likely be neither good nor optimal.

Introduction \(\cdots\) Current lcoal and global explanations \(\cdots\)glex: Unifying local and global explanations \(\cdots\) Open problems

Interpretability Open problems I

  • To simplify notation, assume that \(D\) and \(X\) are one-dimensional and set \[ E[Y| X=x, D=d] = m(x,d) = m_0 + m_x^\ast(x)+ m_d^\ast(d)+ m_{xd}^\ast(x,d).\]
  • \(\Rightarrow\) \(E[Y| do(X=x)] = m^\ast_0+ m^\ast_x(x)\)
  • Interesting:
    • previous slide: estimate a two dimensional regression function marginalise
    • now: estimating a constant (\(\hat h_0\)) and a one-dimensional function (\(\hat h_x(x)\)) under structured regression setting.
  • Implications:
    • The first approach, i.e., estimating a high dimensional regression function first, will most likely suffer from the curse of dimensionality and also will have a non-optimal bias.
      • The second formulation, however, gives hope that the discrimination-free price can be estimated with estimation errors that asymptotically correspond to a one-dimensional regression problem. In the additive case, i.e., for \(h_{xd}(x,d)=0\), this has been shown in Mammen, Linton, and Nielsen (1999). The more complex case with interactions is however up to my knowledge still an open problem. This discussion is related to work done in double/debiased machine learning Chernozhukov et al. (2018).

Interpretability Open problems II

What does discrimination free pricing actually mean?

Average claim Size

Car Male Female
Male Car Type $1 $2
Female Car Type $2 $1

Proportions in population \((p_{X,D})\)

Car Male Female
Male Car Type 0.45 0.05
Female Car Type 0.05 0.45

  • If we marginalize \(p_D(d) = 0.5\) for pricing, then the price for Male Car Type 1 and Female Car Type would be $1.50 each.

  • Problem : The prices are not calibrated now: The insurance company is charging more than the expected average claim size of $1.10 . (We ignore risk loading)

  • We could multiply the price by \(\frac{1.10}{1.50}\approx 0.7333\). Hence charge everyone \(\$1.10\)

  • Problem: Is the price still discrimination free?

    • Note that $1.10 is also the price if we would ignore gender completely, \(E[Y|X=x]\) (i.e. allow for indirect discrimination).

  • The answer will most likely be around the question why we wanted to de-bias for gender in the first place; what are the risk-factors we want to use, and what are unmeasured confounders.

  • In short: We need a causal story.
